acs: Firstly is an idea, once you have that idea for the particular vehicle you are shooting you then film it and see that idea come to life. I don't worry about how many subscribers I have and how many views the video gets. I do it because I enjoy it. .bizicon + br{display:none} h2 .bizicon img{top:10px !important}Comment on the significance of electric mobility and how it will change the automotive landscape in South Africa.Isaacs: Unfortunately, I don't have much experience here, and to speak of this now is too early. We simply don't have the infrastructure yet and electric cars in South Africa are extremely expensive..bizicon + br{display:none} h2 .bizicon img{top:10px !important}I know that you are a devout petrol head. But do you think South African youth need to develop a sense of affection for electric cars? If so, why?Isaacs: I had the opportunity to drive BMW's i3 and I was completely blown away by it. I couldn't believe the acceleration but also how quiet it was. Once the youth start seeing what these cars do at our local race tracks, they are surely going to come round..bizicon + br{display:none} h2 .bizicon img{top:10px !important}What do you think the most important thing is for youth in South Africa when it comes to cars and why?Isaacs: Cars keep youth out of trouble, they stir emotions and put a smile on your face, they keep you away from doing wrong as they keep you occupied. That feeling of your foot on the throttle, lovely exhaust note at the back and a good song on the radio, there is nothing like it. <img src="https://biz-file.com/c/2105/611932.jpg" alt="In conversation with Sabelo Nxele AKA 'The Car Guy'" width="120" height="120">In conversation with Sabelo Nxele AKA 'The Car Guy'Nxele reveals the reason he willingly gives out valuable advice to car buyers on social media. He also tells the short story of his path to the automotive industry...By Ntandokazi Ntozakhe 28 May 2021.bizicon + br{display:none} h2 .bizicon img{top:10px !important}What 